01:45 am. We had the data, and it was time to report. I started the Downlink briefing, and Mobility couldn't stay in the chair. Rich Rieber in his outmost excitements briefed the team on how his mobility system performed. @NASAPersevere drove 6.5 meters for the FIRST time! https://t.co/TQyyvmUKFs

I said to my team, inspired by @POTUS , these kids will not be alone tonight because we are with them & we believe in them. So let's make their day a better day by inspiring them to keep going. I played Lovely Day by @TheWithersBill. I also thought about my best friend @OpalMoon

12:00 AM.The team was there on time, and pushing with excellence all the way. I thought about @POTUS words and reflect with the team on them.  We did the impossible and created dreams along the way to millions of kids whom will be the next generation of scientists and engineers.

11:20 pm. D, are you Flight tonight? Asked Tactical Downlink Lead, Andrew Plave . Myüß†had a minor freak out. Are we late? Nope he said. Andrew was doing his thing, always on top of his game, and tracking with me. Total pleasure to work with that guy since @MarsCuriosity

1:30 pm. I had the honor to join the @NASAPersevere team for a call with @POTUS. His words about how this mission has become a symbol of hope during this pandemic made me reflect. @DrSwatiMohan it was so great to hear your story on the call!! https://t.co/fp2GhF2hHv

And as a very proud member of the @NASA family, it was so cool to see @CaptMarkKelly in his new role as @SenMarkKelly. What a legend. He had kind and very meaningful words I've been delighted to carry back the the @NASAPersevere team. https://t.co/T1InZ5d3nW
It was a wonderful conversation. I was also delighted to have a chance to thank @SenAlexPadilla for appearing on the #JuntosPerseveramos livestream!

Solving some of the most challenging problems in history requires the best brains in the world. And any team built from only one type of people will tend to get lots of the same type of solution. Diversity of *people* leads to diversity of *ideas*.

After providing an update on the status of the rover, most of our conversation focused on the ways that @NASA @NASAJPL have built some of the world's greatest teams by embracing the power of diversity.

I had the incredible opportunity to join NASA's acting administrator Steve Jurczyk and Dr. Lori Glaze, NASA's director of planetary science to speak to 30+ US Senators about our incredible @NASAPersevere team
And later that morning had the amazing opportunity to talk about the importance of diversity! Because you need everyone #JuntosPerseveramos

And then at 01:00 am we got the data. We had done the first wheel checkout where we wiggled the front and rear steer actuators. And we listen to Low Rider because Low Rider/Rich Rieber Mobility Systems Engineer knows every rock https://t.co/dqVTF1wWJo
Thursday 12:30 *AM*. It is in the Flight Director's blood to care for your team, so I woke up the @NASAPersevere team the best way I know. Mariachis at midnight!üá≤üáΩ https://t.co/pYKv2Upp97

It was Sat 3/21/2020. The Robotic Arm system engineer Doug Klein was on the line with me. ‚ÄúLaunch stow restrained completed‚Äù he said and that was the last thing we did on üåé at the cape that day for the Robotic Arm. And now, we see this on Mars on Sol 12 https://t.co/mghQd7Jw9Y

On sol 12, we unstow @NASAPersevere 7 ft arm for the FIRST time, and we saw it go without a glitch. That was simply amazing and unbelievable. I saw the images of the unstow, and it took me back to March 2020. Almost 1 year ago...

Which it takes us to this week. Where should we start? The team, the activities, the music, @POTUS , forgetting what day it is on Earth because you are only thinking Mars Time, the love that you receive from everyone around you and the world, and the love that you give back. https://t.co/cuzfhzAvHy

And it went unbelievably smooth!! We were relief during the Commanding Shift when we heard the nominal beep from the @NASAPersevere confirming that we had transition to surface flight software successfully! https://t.co/8Fsk4sKz5G
If everything is nominal, we spend the next 4 sols committing the main and back up computers to the new software and setting it up in preparation for the next activity
FSW transition is hard. The main computer boots from RAM on the new software, we stay awake until we do the first orbiter UHF pass, and we look at the data‚Ä¶did we fatal? Are we healthy??
Last week we installed the Surface Flight Software in the main computers @NASAPersevere. This was important because it has the capabilities that we needed to do the next amazing things.

Since we landed, we have hit every major milestones with @NASAPersevere with the outmost excellence! Which speaks to the amazing diverse team that we have. #JuntosPerseveramos. https://t.co/p1O0GUnfG6
